00:15.352 --> 00:17.351
WOMAN: <i>Are you ready for this?</i>

00:17.352 --> 00:19.521
What is a pre-interview, anyway?

00:19.522 --> 00:23.231
I think it's just Alison's PR people
reminding us not to say anything idiotic.

00:23.232 --> 00:28.141
All right, but they're not actually
going to interview me, are they?

00:28.142 --> 00:29.731
I don't think so.

00:29.732 --> 00:34.312
You'll be in the family photo, so your
fake-smile game better be on point.

00:35.852 --> 00:37.351
(LAUGHS)

00:37.352 --> 00:40.061
- MAN: <i>You like that?</i>
- <i>Wildly insincere.</i>

00:40.062 --> 00:43.311
- MAN: <i>Well, I know it's not good.</i>
- WOMAN: <i>It's not torture!</i>

00:43.312 --> 00:44.811
MAN: <i>I know.</i>

00:44.812 --> 00:48.182
(RUMBLING, CREAKING)

00:51.562 --> 00:53.311
You have to sell it.

00:53.312 --> 00:55.311
"I love this family!"

00:55.312 --> 00:57.311
"This is not a family of lunatics."

00:57.312 --> 00:58.311
Like this.

00:58.312 --> 01:00.311
Look.

01:00.312 --> 01:01.931
(LAUGHS): Okay.

01:01.932 --> 01:04.062
- <i>Yeah, yeah, that's convincing.</i>
- (LAUGHS)

01:09.642 --> 01:12.522
(HORNS HONKING, TIRES SCREECHING)

01:19.472 --> 01:20.971
WOMAN: <i>Did you hear that?</i>

01:20.972 --> 01:22.431
No. Hear what?

01:22.432 --> 01:24.521
- (ELECTRONIC DING)
- Ovulation app.

01:24.522 --> 01:25.561
(WHOOPS)

01:25.562 --> 01:27.431
Today's the day.

01:27.432 --> 01:28.891
Today's the day.

01:28.892 --> 01:30.771
All right.

01:30.772 --> 01:35.431
Should we do it at my parents' house?
Just to see if we could get away with it?

01:35.432 --> 01:36.931
MAN: <i>No. That's a terrible idea.</i>

01:36.932 --> 01:38.431
WOMAN: <i>Live a little!</i>

01:38.432 --> 01:39.931
<i>Where's your sense of adventure?</i>

01:39.932 --> 01:41.181
(MAN LAUGHING)

01:41.182 --> 01:44.022
- ♪
♪
- (BIRDS CHIRPING)

01:56.369 --> 01:58.369
Did you take Garrett's
picture off the wall?

02:00.677 --> 02:02.507
He's still part of this family.

02:05.522 --> 02:08.640
Just for today, okay?

02:08.642 --> 02:10.352
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

02:11.642 --> 02:14.431
Honey, did you order a walking

02:14.432 --> 02:16.141
- Norman Rockwell painting?
- (LAUGHS)

02:16.142 --> 02:17.471
- Never gets old.
- WOMAN: You girls look so pretty!

02:17.472 --> 02:19.681
MAN: Hi, sweethearts. Here you go.

02:19.682 --> 02:20.971
- Tom, how are you?
- Mitchell.

02:20.972 --> 02:22.931
This is Naomi,

02:22.932 --> 02:24.601
my new campaign manager.

02:24.602 --> 02:27.141
Six weeks to go... I had
to bring in the best.

02:27.142 --> 02:29.471
It's lovely to meet you, Mr. Hawthorne.

02:29.472 --> 02:30.931
- As well.
- Mrs. Hawthorne.

02:30.932 --> 02:32.182
Please, come in.

02:35.272 --> 02:37.431
It's stunning.

02:37.432 --> 02:38.471
Thank you.

02:38.472 --> 02:40.311
Ali, your brother just got here.

02:40.312 --> 02:42.181
♪ ♪

02:42.182 --> 02:43.521
- Hey.
- Hey.

02:43.522 --> 02:45.932
- How are you, Cam?
- Oh, peachy.

02:49.812 --> 02:51.471
- You look good.
- Mm.

02:51.472 --> 02:53.641
Yeah.

02:53.642 --> 02:55.311
- Where's Tessa?
- WOMAN: We're here!

02:55.312 --> 02:56.851
(LAUGHS): We're here, we're here.

02:56.852 --> 02:58.602
NAOMI: <i>It is wonderful to meet you all.</i>

02:59.642 --> 03:03.311
Now, as you know, it is never
easy to unseat the incumbent.

03:03.312 --> 03:05.219
Even when he really deserves it.

03:05.244 --> 03:09.833
So, the objective here is to invite the
press in to get to know the Hawthornes.

03:10.005 --> 03:12.085
The people of your district
love their city councilor.

03:14.032 --> 03:15.441
We need the people of Boston

03:15.442 --> 03:19.481
to love their potential
new mayor and her family.

03:19.482 --> 03:23.441
The key is keeping you relatable
to working-class constituents

03:23.442 --> 03:25.361
who are growing disillusioned
with Mayor Conley.

03:25.362 --> 03:27.401
This family grew up working-class.

03:27.402 --> 03:29.651
Tessa's a teacher and
Brady's a police officer...

03:29.652 --> 03:31.481
He actually just made detective.

03:31.482 --> 03:32.981
- Congratulations! That's fantastic!
- Oh, that's wonderful!

03:32.982 --> 03:35.401
And you know what else?
Right here we have

03:35.402 --> 03:36.941
the creator of <i>Roger's Cube.</i>

03:36.942 --> 03:38.611
An icon of the everyman.

03:38.612 --> 03:41.111
And this is the first
strip ever published.

03:41.112 --> 03:44.031
He would read the comics every day
and then draw his own beside them.

03:44.032 --> 03:47.611
Now he's syndicated in 85 newspapers.

03:47.612 --> 03:50.231
You gonna be an artist like your dad?

03:50.232 --> 03:53.111
Actually, I want to be
a medical examiner.

03:53.112 --> 03:55.482
For the autopsies.

03:57.862 --> 04:00.111
He's going through a phase.

04:00.112 --> 04:05.441
So... are there any other rooms
that are not quite as grand?

04:05.442 --> 04:08.861
Sure. Um, we'll show you around.

04:08.862 --> 04:10.861
Right now.

04:10.862 --> 04:12.271
Okay.

04:12.272 --> 04:13.611
Shh, shh, shh.

04:13.612 --> 04:15.901
(WHISPERS): Are you sure about this?

04:15.902 --> 04:18.271
- Ah, Tess.
- Shh...

04:18.272 --> 04:20.692
This could work.

04:22.942 --> 04:25.611
So, let's say I'm the interviewer.

04:25.612 --> 04:27.191
Tell me about your career.

04:27.192 --> 04:30.031
Sure. Well, uh, I'm an
entrepreneur now, and...

04:30.032 --> 04:31.271
No.

04:31.272 --> 04:32.611
You started your own business.

04:32.612 --> 04:34.441
You work in construction.

04:34.442 --> 04:37.191
We need to tap into the people
that you were 20 years ago,

04:37.192 --> 04:40.691
before Hawthorne Concrete
of Boston became...

04:40.692 --> 04:42.941
Is that an original Pollock?

04:42.942 --> 04:44.072
Yes, it is.

04:45.692 --> 04:48.271
This isn't gonna work.
It's too extravagant.

04:48.272 --> 04:50.441
We need a change of venue.

04:50.442 --> 04:53.271
What are you thinking? Stick
to campaign headquarters?

04:53.272 --> 04:55.402
That's our best bet.

04:56.772 --> 04:58.771
(WHISPERS): Someone's coming.

04:58.772 --> 05:00.401
Not yet. Not yet.

05:00.402 --> 05:01.981
- (OBJECTS CLACKING, RATTLING)
- Tess...

05:01.982 --> 05:04.771
So... the little boy,
the budding coroner...

05:04.772 --> 05:06.361
where's Mom?

05:06.362 --> 05:07.861
Come on.

05:07.862 --> 05:09.861
I need to know where all
the bodies are buried.

05:09.862 --> 05:12.981
She and Cam met in art school, bonded
over their deep love of drugs,

05:12.982 --> 05:14.611
and along came Jack.

05:14.612 --> 05:16.821
Cam finally got clean last
year and is divorcing Sophie,

05:16.822 --> 05:18.941
who hasn't been clean for
more than five minutes

05:18.942 --> 05:20.611
for as long as I've known her.

05:20.612 --> 05:21.821
- (OBJECTS CLATTER)
- Shh...

05:21.822 --> 05:24.272
Is somebody in there?

05:25.322 --> 05:26.771
Hey!

05:26.772 --> 05:28.441
We were just scrounging
around for a snack.

05:28.442 --> 05:29.861
(CLEARS THROAT)

05:29.862 --> 05:31.861
- NAOMI: Oh, quick question, Detective.
- Mm.

05:31.862 --> 05:35.151
Do you still have a regular police
uniform you could wear for the photo op?

05:35.152 --> 05:36.821
No. They, uh, they actually
make you turn those back in.

05:36.822 --> 05:39.191
- Ah. That's too bad.
- Hello.

05:39.192 --> 05:41.481
- Yeah.
- Just keep in mind that luxury reads

05:41.482 --> 05:43.271
on camera, so don't wear
any articles of clothing

05:43.272 --> 05:44.531
that cost more than a hundred dollars.

05:44.532 --> 05:45.531
Not a problem.

05:45.532 --> 05:46.861
Also, your fly's down.

05:46.862 --> 05:49.361
My... uh...

05:49.362 --> 05:51.772
Naomi. We have an issue.

05:53.482 --> 05:55.941
(BOTH LAUGHING)

05:55.942 --> 05:59.941
Part of the ceiling collapsed
in a tunnel on the expressway.

05:59.942 --> 06:02.071
Tell me Hawthorne Concrete didn't
supply that part of the tunnel.

06:02.072 --> 06:04.321
I wish I could.

06:04.322 --> 06:06.271
Conley's gonna be all over this.

06:06.272 --> 06:07.941
Yeah. This could be worse

06:07.942 --> 06:09.981
<i>than the '06 collapse.</i>

06:09.982 --> 06:12.322
(SIREN WAILING, INDISTINCT
RADIO TRANSMISSION)

06:16.572 --> 06:19.942
♪ ♪

06:22.112 --> 06:24.271
Is that a belt?

06:24.272 --> 06:26.692
(SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE)

06:39.982 --> 06:42.321
(INDISTINCT CHATTER, PHONES RINGING)

06:42.322 --> 06:44.571
I know, I know. Unbelievable.

06:44.572 --> 06:46.611
Hmm. Happy hour start early in here?

06:46.612 --> 06:48.651
Big find in the tunnel collapse.

06:48.652 --> 06:51.191
A belt? How'd a belt
get inside the tunnel?

06:51.192 --> 06:54.401
Guessing somebody disposed of it
after they used it in a murder.

06:54.402 --> 06:56.861
Now, the prints come back to this guy.

06:56.862 --> 06:59.321
He must have left it on the
belt when he fought back.

06:59.322 --> 07:01.441
Name's David Morales.

07:01.442 --> 07:03.731
- Does that ring a bell?
- Uh-uh.

07:03.732 --> 07:06.402
Brady, come on. A <i>silver</i> bell, maybe.

07:07.612 --> 07:09.821
Yeah. Exactly.

07:09.822 --> 07:11.401
I ran forensics on it.

07:11.402 --> 07:13.271
A lot of stuff we got to cover.

07:13.272 --> 07:15.941
We need coffees. Let's go.

07:15.942 --> 07:18.272
♪ ♪

07:21.572 --> 07:23.071
ALISON: A man's belt?

07:23.072 --> 07:25.271
BRADY: Yeah. The prints on it

07:25.272 --> 07:27.821
match one of the victims of
the Silver Bells Killer.

07:27.822 --> 07:30.071
They're running it for DNA now.

07:30.072 --> 07:31.731
Oh, my God.

07:31.732 --> 07:33.481
We've never had a Silver
Bells murder weapon.

07:33.482 --> 07:35.771
It's the biggest lead
on this case in years.

07:35.772 --> 07:37.771
I thought you'd want to know ASAP.

07:37.772 --> 07:40.571
- Absolutely. Thank you.
- Of course.

07:40.572 --> 07:42.651
And, uh, Alison.

07:42.652 --> 07:46.441
Catching this case would
be a career-maker for me.

07:46.442 --> 07:49.571
So if you happen to find
yourself on the phone

07:49.572 --> 07:52.901
- with the commissioner...
- Of course.

07:52.902 --> 07:54.441
(BEEPS)

07:54.442 --> 07:57.271
We have an opportunity.

07:57.272 --> 07:59.571
Stunning break tonight in
the case of the elusive

07:59.572 --> 08:01.901
serial killer known as Silver Bells.

08:01.902 --> 08:04.361
Rubble from the recent tunnel collapse

08:04.362 --> 08:09.111
revealed evidence connected to
a victim killed back in 2002.

08:09.112 --> 08:11.231
...a killer known for
strangling his victims

08:11.232 --> 08:13.571
and leaving no trace at the scene

08:13.572 --> 08:15.861
except for his eerie calling card:

08:15.862 --> 08:18.111
a small silver handbell.

08:18.112 --> 08:20.361
...six victims from 1999 to 2002,

08:20.362 --> 08:22.441
before the murders abruptly stopped

08:22.442 --> 08:23.941
and the case went cold.

08:23.942 --> 08:26.611
Many of you remember the terror

08:26.612 --> 08:29.191
that gripped our city during that time.

08:29.192 --> 08:31.151
I certainly do.

08:31.152 --> 08:34.321
Though the murders stopped,
the fear has never gone away,

08:34.322 --> 08:38.902
and it won't... until the Silver
Bells Killer is behind bars.

08:40.572 --> 08:42.821
Unfortunately, we haven't
got any closer to that

08:42.822 --> 08:44.231
under Mayor Conley's watch.

08:44.232 --> 08:45.691
But if I am your mayor,

08:45.692 --> 08:47.691
I will make it my mission to work

08:47.692 --> 08:50.691
with law enforcement to crack
this case once and for all,

08:50.692 --> 08:52.531
so that the citizens of Boston

08:52.532 --> 08:54.071
- (SOFT GRUNTING)
- can sleep easy knowing that...

08:54.072 --> 08:56.651
- Mitch!
- Dad!

08:56.652 --> 08:58.481
- (EXCITED CHATTER)
- Dad? Are you all right?

08:58.482 --> 09:00.191
- Somebody call 911.
- Call 911!

09:00.192 --> 09:02.032
(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

09:03.272 --> 09:04.942
(CROWD CLAMORING)

09:08.732 --> 09:12.923
- sync and corrections by Caio -
- www.addic7ed.com -

09:22.540 --> 09:24.709
ALISON: He was worried
about the tunnel collapse.

09:24.709 --> 09:26.039
Uh, w-we don't know that.

09:26.064 --> 09:28.708
He was. I should have emphasized

09:28.709 --> 09:30.352
it was just the bolts, nothing to do

09:30.383 --> 09:32.632
- with our family's concrete...
- Hey, Ali, I know the world

09:32.633 --> 09:35.000
typically revolves around
you, but I'm pretty sure

09:35.008 --> 09:37.660
your press conference didn't
cause Dad's heart attack.

09:37.662 --> 09:41.281
Actually, extreme stress can
trigger cardiac arrest.

09:41.282 --> 09:45.322
Jack, why don't you go
play with the twins?

09:46.322 --> 09:48.071
Do you know

09:48.072 --> 09:50.821
how many different microbes
could be on that floor?

09:50.822 --> 09:53.071
I think we should tell Garrett.

09:53.072 --> 09:54.821
It's his father, too.

09:54.822 --> 09:56.571
He should know what's going on.

09:56.572 --> 09:58.911
Well, what do <i>you</i> think?

09:58.912 --> 10:01.281
I think if he really cared,

10:01.282 --> 10:03.491
he would have left a forwarding address.

10:03.492 --> 10:05.992
Or at least a phone number.

10:08.242 --> 10:09.781
Oh, no.

10:09.782 --> 10:11.911
♪ ♪

10:11.912 --> 10:13.242
No.

10:15.112 --> 10:16.821
Hey, Mom.

10:16.822 --> 10:18.821
(CHUCKLES): Hey, baby.

10:18.822 --> 10:20.991
What are you doing here?

10:20.992 --> 10:25.571
SOPHIE: I heard on the news
he had a heart attack.

10:25.572 --> 10:27.161
You should not be here.

10:27.162 --> 10:28.911
Cam, I just wanted

10:28.912 --> 10:30.781
to be here for you.

10:30.782 --> 10:33.911
Supporting you.

10:33.912 --> 10:36.161
Look...

10:36.162 --> 10:38.161
we'll get through this, okay?

10:38.162 --> 10:40.161
And then maybe we can talk about

10:40.162 --> 10:42.322
giving us another shot.

10:46.452 --> 10:49.822
- Cam.
- This is over, Soph.

10:52.662 --> 10:54.662
It has to be.

10:57.492 --> 10:58.951
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

10:58.952 --> 11:00.951
(LINE RINGING)

11:00.952 --> 11:03.281
(SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE)

11:03.282 --> 11:04.741
MAN: Hunting Hut. Closed now.

11:04.742 --> 11:06.321
- Uh, wait, please.
- Call back in the...

11:06.322 --> 11:08.411
This is Garrett
Hawthorne's sister Tessa.

11:08.412 --> 11:10.491
Yeah, I remember you.
You called once before.

11:10.492 --> 11:13.491
You as hot as you sound on the phone?

11:13.492 --> 11:15.991
Our dad just had a massive
heart attack and we don't know

11:15.992 --> 11:17.491
if he's gonna make it.

11:17.492 --> 11:19.492
Give Garrett the message.

11:21.912 --> 11:24.162
(BEEPS)

11:34.162 --> 11:37.411
(SIGHS)

11:37.412 --> 11:40.201
(DOOR OPENS)

11:40.202 --> 11:43.321
I'm here, Mitch. We're all here.

11:43.322 --> 11:45.991
(WEAKLY): The tunnel.

11:45.992 --> 11:47.491
That wasn't your fault...

11:47.492 --> 11:50.412
it was defective bolt anchors.

11:51.742 --> 11:53.991
I'm sorry.

11:53.992 --> 11:56.991
Shh. Honey, don't talk.

11:56.992 --> 11:59.201
You need your rest.

11:59.202 --> 12:01.411
Mom wants to spend the
night here, with him.

12:01.412 --> 12:04.071
I think we should stay at the
house for the next few days.

12:04.072 --> 12:06.284
She's gonna need support
once she gets back.

12:06.309 --> 12:07.032
Yeah, sure.

12:07.072 --> 12:10.491
Jack and I are staying at the house, too.
You know, till Soph finds a new place.

12:10.492 --> 12:14.871
Great. So, maybe we'll all be together.

12:14.872 --> 12:16.451
Oh.

12:16.452 --> 12:18.201
I'll be at my house.

12:18.202 --> 12:20.202
But thanks.

12:24.822 --> 12:27.242
(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

12:35.372 --> 12:37.372
♪ ♪

12:44.032 --> 12:46.412
(DOOR OPENS)

12:49.702 --> 12:51.661
- TESSA: Hey.
- (CLATTERING)

12:51.662 --> 12:52.661
Oh,

12:52.662 --> 12:53.701
geez, you scared me.

12:53.702 --> 12:55.111
What are you doing out here?

12:55.112 --> 12:58.411
I'm just looking around.

12:58.412 --> 12:59.871
For what?

12:59.872 --> 13:01.701
Uh, pictures and stuff.

13:01.702 --> 13:05.321
I thought I'd maybe bring
it by the hospital.

13:05.322 --> 13:08.951
Do you have a stash out here?

13:08.952 --> 13:11.702
What? No.

13:13.612 --> 13:15.951
It's just weed.

13:15.952 --> 13:18.161
Don't lie to me.

13:18.162 --> 13:19.702
It's not just weed.

13:21.662 --> 13:23.781
Why would you, Cam?

13:23.782 --> 13:25.161
Why?

13:25.162 --> 13:27.992
You've made it almost a year.

13:29.992 --> 13:32.821
Surprise, Tess, I'm a huge screwup.

13:32.822 --> 13:36.201
Look. I'm not Alison, okay?
I'm not gonna yell at you.

13:36.202 --> 13:38.951
I'm not gonna judge you.

13:38.952 --> 13:42.162
I'll help you find the drugs,
and we'll throw them out.

13:48.032 --> 13:50.032
Thank you.

13:53.282 --> 13:56.821
ONE SMALL POINT: I actually
have no idea where I put 'em.

13:56.822 --> 13:59.162
(SIGHS)

14:13.662 --> 14:15.071
Maybe I was thinking

14:15.072 --> 14:17.451
of the toolshed at the
house down the Cape.

14:17.452 --> 14:19.951
Cam, if you think I'm gonna
give up and go to bed

14:19.952 --> 14:22.451
so you can find your stash and use,

14:22.452 --> 14:24.452
you can dream on.

14:31.572 --> 14:34.661
I don't think I would've
put it in Dad's stuff.

14:34.662 --> 14:37.492
Well, you never know.

14:41.742 --> 14:43.162
(JINGLING)

14:55.492 --> 14:57.202
(JINGLING)

14:58.702 --> 15:01.201
(GASPS)

15:01.202 --> 15:03.202
Oh, my God.

15:22.921 --> 15:24.866
This can't be what it looks like.

15:24.905 --> 15:25.994
- No.
- No.

15:25.995 --> 15:27.324
- Of course not.
- Of course not.

15:27.325 --> 15:29.864
No.

15:29.865 --> 15:32.654
So what's the explanation?

15:32.655 --> 15:34.324
I mean, the box looks old.

15:34.325 --> 15:39.074
It could have been here
before we even moved in.

15:39.249 --> 15:42.369
So, what, we bought the house
from the Silver Bells Killer?

15:44.329 --> 15:45.908
I should tell Brady.

15:45.909 --> 15:47.408
He's on the case.

15:47.409 --> 15:49.038
He should be investigating
the previous owner.

15:49.039 --> 15:50.539
Oh, my God.

15:51.749 --> 15:53.749
Wait.

15:55.169 --> 15:57.169
This is our newspaper.

15:58.909 --> 16:01.369
I drew this.

16:03.329 --> 16:04.908
Why?

16:04.909 --> 16:07.248
Why would Dad cut these out?

16:07.249 --> 16:09.288
Okay, look...

16:09.289 --> 16:11.328
Look, the Silver Bells
case was everywhere.

16:11.329 --> 16:13.618
I mean, it was all over
the news, right? I mean,

16:13.619 --> 16:15.958
people got fixated on it,
became amateur sleuths,

16:15.959 --> 16:17.748
tried to crack the case.
Dad could have done that.

16:17.749 --> 16:20.748
I mean, he was into
that true crime stuff.

16:20.749 --> 16:23.788
Maybe that explains the
articles, but the bells?

16:23.789 --> 16:27.288
I don't know. Lo-Look, we'll...
talk to Mom tomorrow.

16:27.289 --> 16:29.828
Dad, if he's up to it.

16:29.829 --> 16:31.748
Okay?

16:31.749 --> 16:33.169
Okay.

16:34.829 --> 16:37.579
God, I could really use
that fix right now.

16:40.909 --> 16:42.909
You and me both.

16:43.959 --> 16:46.289
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

17:01.169 --> 17:02.958
Morning, bud.

17:02.959 --> 17:04.458
Morning.

17:04.459 --> 17:06.248
Can I show you my drawings?

17:06.249 --> 17:07.959
Yeah, sure thing.

17:12.669 --> 17:15.117
What you got?

17:15.118 --> 17:17.367
This is someone with a heart attack,

17:17.368 --> 17:19.868
like Grandpa, if he died.

17:22.289 --> 17:26.288
Wow. That's really detailed.

17:26.289 --> 17:28.289
I'm impressed.

17:31.039 --> 17:32.368
This one got strangled.

17:32.369 --> 17:35.079
Like what Silver Bells does.

17:38.329 --> 17:39.828
How do you know about that?

17:39.829 --> 17:41.369
I borrowed Grandpa's iPad.

17:43.869 --> 17:47.788
It's really interesting, because
the ligature marks indicate

17:47.789 --> 17:49.668
- that the victim...
- What if you

17:49.669 --> 17:51.748
drew a picture of a man

17:51.749 --> 17:54.248
who could grow wings and fly?

17:54.249 --> 17:55.998
People can't fly.

17:55.999 --> 17:57.368
That's not real.

17:57.369 --> 17:58.708
Roger's not real,

17:58.709 --> 18:01.409
and he's still fun to draw.

18:04.669 --> 18:06.668
This one got disemboweled.

18:06.669 --> 18:08.749
That's where all the guts come out.

18:24.119 --> 18:26.579
(KEYBOARD CLICKING)

18:35.409 --> 18:37.409
♪ ♪

18:47.209 --> 18:49.209
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

18:53.749 --> 18:55.578
Have you seen Caramel?

18:55.579 --> 18:57.408
- What?
- My cat,

18:57.409 --> 18:58.868
Caramel. He's missing.

18:58.869 --> 18:59.869
Have you seen him?

19:01.579 --> 19:03.408
He's the color of caramel.

19:03.409 --> 19:06.958
Oh, uh, no. I'm sorry.

19:06.959 --> 19:09.909
Uh, I'll keep an eye out for him, okay?

19:17.119 --> 19:18.908
Can I help you?

19:18.909 --> 19:22.169
Hey, little sister.

19:23.499 --> 19:25.498
Oh, my God.

19:25.499 --> 19:27.499
Garrett?

19:31.459 --> 19:33.408
Oh, my God.

19:33.409 --> 19:36.709
How you doing, Tess?

19:38.169 --> 19:40.288
How are you?

19:40.289 --> 19:43.668
I'm good. Good.

19:43.669 --> 19:45.288
How are you?

19:45.289 --> 19:47.668
You know.

19:47.669 --> 19:49.168
So, you got my message.

19:49.169 --> 19:50.669
Yeah.

19:52.079 --> 19:53.578
How is he?

19:53.579 --> 19:56.498
Holding up.

19:56.499 --> 19:57.998
- It's been a bit scary.
- (DOOR OPENS)

19:57.999 --> 20:00.748
- (DOOR CLOSES)
- I'm so glad you came.

20:00.749 --> 20:03.579
Holy crap.

20:05.209 --> 20:06.669
How you doing, Cam?

20:08.169 --> 20:10.619
We were just about to go to
the hospital to see Dad.

20:12.669 --> 20:15.408
Okay.

20:15.409 --> 20:18.169
I'll give you a ride.

20:27.539 --> 20:30.368
So...

20:30.369 --> 20:33.619
what've you been up to, Garrett?

20:35.539 --> 20:38.538
I've been living in Maine.

20:38.539 --> 20:41.619
Reading a lot of books.

20:45.959 --> 20:48.789
Missed you at my wedding.

20:51.329 --> 20:53.958
I got married, too.

20:53.959 --> 20:56.288
You got to be kidding me.

20:56.289 --> 20:58.498
How old are you now anyway?

20:58.499 --> 21:01.249
I'm 27.

21:02.289 --> 21:04.538
Where'd the time go?

21:04.539 --> 21:06.668
Where did <i>you</i> go?

21:06.669 --> 21:10.169
I already told you that.

21:15.039 --> 21:16.409
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

21:17.999 --> 21:20.669
Look who we hitched a ride with.

21:30.249 --> 21:32.668
MADELINE: You're here.

21:32.669 --> 21:35.249
I don't believe it.

21:37.539 --> 21:40.079
You're here.

21:43.909 --> 21:46.669
Mom.

21:54.079 --> 21:57.368
Ali.

21:57.369 --> 22:00.578
Wow. You, uh... you look fancy.

22:00.579 --> 22:03.408
What are you doing here?

22:03.409 --> 22:06.909
Oh, you know, just picking
up a prescription.

22:08.249 --> 22:10.828
Well, these are my daughters,

22:10.829 --> 22:12.168
Harper and Violet.

22:12.169 --> 22:14.749
- Hi.
- You have a big beard.

22:35.079 --> 22:37.249
Hey, old man.

22:40.829 --> 22:42.669
(GRUNTING SOFTLY)

22:46.119 --> 22:49.078
He-he just shows up like it's nothing?

22:49.079 --> 22:52.248
(SPEAKING QUIETLY)

22:52.249 --> 22:54.078
(QUIETLY): We have to
tell Mom what we found.

22:54.079 --> 22:56.498
- I can't get it out of my head.
- (ERRATIC BEEPING)

22:56.499 --> 22:58.618
And if you don't do
that, then I'm gonna...

22:58.619 --> 23:03.078
- (RAPID BEEPING)
- (ALARM SOUNDING)

23:03.079 --> 23:04.288
TESSA: Dad.

23:04.289 --> 23:05.618
- ALISON: Dad?
- Everybody clear the room!

23:05.619 --> 23:08.038
TESSA: My God.

23:08.039 --> 23:10.538
- Dad. Mom, what do we do?
- Right away, please! Right now.

23:10.539 --> 23:13.168
- Thank you!
- Mom, come on. - Mom.

23:13.169 --> 23:15.538
- Paddles. Clear.
- (WHIRRING)

23:15.539 --> 23:16.538
- (BEEPING)
- (GRUNTS)

23:16.539 --> 23:17.908
Again.

23:17.909 --> 23:20.329
(WHIRRING, BEEPING, ZAP)

23:32.180 --> 23:34.100
What did you say?

23:36.594 --> 23:40.213
Right before the alarms started
beeping, you whispered to him.

23:41.211 --> 23:42.881
What was it?

23:44.664 --> 23:46.663
I told him

23:46.664 --> 23:51.243
that I was glad to see him...

23:51.244 --> 23:53.874
and that I loved him.

23:55.461 --> 23:57.290
I'm glad you got a chance to say that.

23:58.141 --> 23:59.681
MADELINE: You're talking like he's dead.

24:01.922 --> 24:03.156
He's not dead.

24:03.211 --> 24:05.663
Yeah, vegetative state's pretty close.

24:05.688 --> 24:07.649
MADELINE: Nobody has used those words.

24:08.228 --> 24:10.557
They said "coma."

24:10.558 --> 24:12.978
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

24:19.308 --> 24:21.647
There's still no sign of Caramel.

24:21.648 --> 24:23.406
So I made flyers.

24:23.625 --> 24:27.494
You could help by distributing
them around the neighborhood.

24:27.495 --> 24:29.335
This is a very traumatic time for me.

24:30.844 --> 24:33.214
My condolences.

24:36.844 --> 24:38.695
TESSA: Are you staying here, Garrett?

24:39.047 --> 24:41.256
I'm sure you could
stay in your old room.

24:41.257 --> 24:43.046
GARRETT: No, I'll sleep out back.

24:43.047 --> 24:44.886
In the shed?

24:44.887 --> 24:46.216
- Not a good idea.
- No.

24:46.217 --> 24:47.636
Why not?

24:47.637 --> 24:49.716
CAM: There's no running water.

24:49.717 --> 24:51.136
No heat.

24:51.137 --> 24:52.426
I'm used to that.

24:52.427 --> 24:53.886
TESSA: There are boxes everywhere.

24:53.977 --> 24:56.346
- There's no room.
- Yeah, you can have a cot down cellar

24:56.347 --> 24:58.516
- if you really want to deprive yourself.
- (FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

24:58.517 --> 24:59.726
Don't be silly.

24:59.727 --> 25:02.017
You can have your old room.

25:04.307 --> 25:06.347
(HINGES CREAKING)

25:27.267 --> 25:29.267
(HINGES CREAK)

25:30.267 --> 25:32.227
(HINGES CREAKING)

25:47.347 --> 25:49.767
You're weird.

25:53.057 --> 25:54.727
All right.

25:56.727 --> 25:58.436
It's okay.

25:58.437 --> 26:00.436
I'm weird, too.

26:00.437 --> 26:04.726
Did you know cicadas spend
17 years underground,

26:04.727 --> 26:07.476
and then emerge and
immediately shed their shell?

26:07.477 --> 26:09.886
They spend all that time building it,

26:09.887 --> 26:11.767
and then just leave it behind.

26:14.177 --> 26:16.766
Do you know...

26:16.767 --> 26:18.806
that if you cut a worm in half,

26:18.807 --> 26:21.017
both sides stay alive?

26:26.677 --> 26:28.346
Jack.

26:28.347 --> 26:31.177
Let me talk to your Uncle
Garrett for a minute, okay?

26:40.597 --> 26:43.017
You said you'd never come back.

26:45.307 --> 26:48.177
I did.

26:53.597 --> 26:55.307
(DOOR CLOSES)

26:59.347 --> 27:00.846
Can you keep a secret?

27:00.847 --> 27:03.676
Sure.

27:03.677 --> 27:05.016
(GROANS)

27:05.017 --> 27:06.266
We found...

27:06.267 --> 27:09.516
unknown DNA on the belt.

27:09.517 --> 27:11.226
And if that matches
someone in the system,

27:11.227 --> 27:14.346
then we have our Silver Bells suspect.

27:14.347 --> 27:15.557
(SOFT CHUCKLE)

27:18.177 --> 27:21.386
So what are these serial
killer types like usually?

27:21.387 --> 27:23.886
What do you mean?

27:23.887 --> 27:26.016
Do they look like...

27:26.017 --> 27:28.016
you know, like, the movie
version of a madman,

27:28.017 --> 27:31.596
or do they seem like
just regular people?

27:31.597 --> 27:33.386
It varies, you know.

27:33.387 --> 27:34.799
A lot of them do look the part.

27:35.042 --> 27:36.916
They're, uh... they're creepy.

27:36.916 --> 27:39.705
They're antisocial types.

27:39.707 --> 27:41.746
But then there are always guys like BTK.

27:43.558 --> 27:44.847
"Bind, Torture, Kill."

27:45.120 --> 27:46.737
His MO.

27:46.886 --> 27:50.225
The crazy thing about him is that
he was deacon in his church.

27:50.683 --> 27:52.432
And a Scout leader.

27:52.432 --> 27:56.842
Just a regular family man, so
no one ever would've guessed.

28:00.682 --> 28:03.722
(CROW CAWING IN THE DISTANCE)

28:33.222 --> 28:35.602
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

28:46.472 --> 28:48.801
Would you like a razor?

28:48.802 --> 28:50.221
No.

28:50.222 --> 28:51.721
(WATER SLOSHING)

28:51.722 --> 28:53.642
I'm used to this.

28:58.932 --> 29:02.181
♪ ♪

29:03.155 --> 29:04.815
Okay, look.

29:06.248 --> 29:08.367
The Silver Bells murders

29:08.368 --> 29:11.037
suddenly stopped 14 years ago.

29:11.038 --> 29:14.327
Do you remember what else
happened 14 years ago?

29:14.328 --> 29:16.658
Garrett left.

29:18.198 --> 29:20.367
What if that's why he marooned himself

29:20.368 --> 29:22.077
out in the middle of nowhere?

29:22.078 --> 29:23.907
To stop himself.

29:23.908 --> 29:27.077
No, there has to be
some other explanation.

29:27.079 --> 29:31.038
When we were kids, Garrett
was the sweetest.

29:31.038 --> 29:33.537
He was the best guy.

29:33.538 --> 29:35.407
He was homecoming king, remember?
Tessa...

29:35.408 --> 29:38.407
- He was gonna marry Molly and have kids.
- Tessa.

29:38.408 --> 29:40.309
- I-I mean, it doesn't make...
- Tessa.

29:40.334 --> 29:44.044
He was in the kitchen shaving
with a hunting knife.

29:46.004 --> 29:48.043
I just don't know what
to do at this point.

29:48.044 --> 29:49.771
We need a strategic thinker.

29:49.881 --> 29:51.733
It'll be toxic for all of us.

29:51.795 --> 29:53.981
Even if it turns out to be baseless.

29:54.006 --> 29:56.385
Has to be some kind of sick joke.

29:56.386 --> 29:58.334
God, I hope so.

29:58.592 --> 30:00.171
You know what?

30:00.196 --> 30:03.655
This could just be some elaborate
setup by Conley for all we know.

30:03.656 --> 30:05.195
- What do you mean?
- Well, think about it.

30:05.196 --> 30:07.485
This hits the press,

30:07.486 --> 30:10.035
it destroys Dad's legacy,

30:10.036 --> 30:11.695
which destroys my campaign.

30:11.696 --> 30:13.695
But look.

30:13.696 --> 30:16.156
This is our newspaper from 1999.

30:18.446 --> 30:21.035
Conley couldn't have planted it.

30:22.185 --> 30:24.925
Oh, God.

30:26.075 --> 30:27.744
Okay.

30:27.745 --> 30:29.418
Have you talked to Brady about this?

30:29.536 --> 30:31.405
- Not yet, but I...
- Don't.

30:31.406 --> 30:33.825
But what if it's true?

30:33.826 --> 30:35.985
What if Dad...

30:35.986 --> 30:38.825
Come on. It's not possible.

30:38.826 --> 30:41.075
Our dad?

30:41.076 --> 30:43.535
The guy who dressed up as
the Chicken Soup Fairy

30:43.536 --> 30:45.485
to cheer us up when we were sick?

30:45.486 --> 30:48.196
What if it's Garrett?

30:50.906 --> 30:53.035
He fits the profile more.

30:53.036 --> 30:56.365
Listen to me. It's not
anybody in this family.

30:56.366 --> 30:58.825
There's another explanation.

30:58.826 --> 31:00.325
Has to be.

31:00.326 --> 31:02.365
You know what this is.

31:02.366 --> 31:04.745
It's a November 6 problem.

31:04.746 --> 31:07.075
Just put the box back.

31:07.076 --> 31:09.825
Don't destroy it, don't move it,

31:09.826 --> 31:11.575
don't mention it.

31:11.576 --> 31:13.485
Just leave it here, and
we'll come find it again

31:13.486 --> 31:15.115
on November 6 and deal with it then.

31:15.116 --> 31:16.655
But if we know something,

31:16.656 --> 31:19.575
we have a moral obligation
to come forward.

31:19.576 --> 31:21.655
This is a serial killer.

31:21.656 --> 31:24.655
No. It's a weird box of bells.

31:24.656 --> 31:26.865
We don't know what it means.

31:26.866 --> 31:28.865
This will be toxic for all of us

31:28.866 --> 31:31.325
even if it turns out to be baseless.

31:31.326 --> 31:33.865
You think the public schools
are gonna keep a teacher

31:33.866 --> 31:37.195
who's possibly related to
the Silver Bells Killer?

31:37.196 --> 31:40.865
Or all of your newspapers are
gonna keep running your comic

31:40.866 --> 31:44.485
with this albatross around your neck?

31:44.486 --> 31:46.785
So, do we agree?

31:46.786 --> 31:48.826
We'll leave it alone for now?

31:50.076 --> 31:52.535
Yeah.

31:52.536 --> 31:54.865
Cam?

31:54.867 --> 31:56.366
You agree?

31:56.367 --> 31:57.987
- Yeah.
- Okay.

32:19.407 --> 32:21.907
(PANTING)

32:23.077 --> 32:25.407
(CAT YOWLING)

32:32.577 --> 32:34.576
(YOWLING, METALLIC RATTLING)

32:36.119 --> 32:37.241
What did you do?

32:37.515 --> 32:39.184
An experiment.

32:39.185 --> 32:41.685
Garden shears can cut through bone.

32:45.210 --> 32:46.709
(ENGINE REVVING)

32:46.710 --> 32:49.553
JACK: <i>Why are you so mad at me?</i>

32:49.686 --> 32:51.331
It was just an experiment.

32:51.332 --> 32:53.951
That's what scientists do.

32:53.952 --> 32:58.082
Because you hurt Caramel,
and that's not okay.

33:04.162 --> 33:06.831
- Hey, Dad?
- Yeah.

33:06.832 --> 33:09.582
Can I watch the vet
sew the tail back on?

33:13.412 --> 33:15.831
(NEEDLES CLICKING QUIETLY)

33:15.832 --> 33:18.252
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

33:27.752 --> 33:30.162
(KNOCKING)

33:33.412 --> 33:35.201
Can you do me a favor?

33:35.202 --> 33:36.991
Sure.

33:36.992 --> 33:40.331
Uh, Jack's in bed, but can
you just keep an eye on him?

33:40.332 --> 33:41.701
Okay. Why?

33:41.702 --> 33:44.161
Wh... where are you going?

33:44.162 --> 33:46.581
I just really want to go see Dad.

33:46.582 --> 33:49.331
I think that it might
help with, you know...

33:49.332 --> 33:50.661
I don't know.

33:50.662 --> 33:52.831
(CLOCK TICKING)

33:52.832 --> 33:55.252
I'm sure Mom would love the company.

33:56.492 --> 33:57.702
Thanks.

34:00.702 --> 34:03.992
(CLOCK TICKING)

34:12.161 --> 34:14.792
(DISTANT SIREN BLARING)

34:17.702 --> 34:20.661
(HINGES CREAKING)

34:20.661 --> 34:22.041
Ten more minutes, and then

34:22.042 --> 34:24.041
lights out, okay?

34:24.042 --> 34:26.042
Okay.

34:29.831 --> 34:31.251
(GASPS)

34:31.252 --> 34:34.081
You scared me.

34:34.081 --> 34:36.081
(SIGHS)

34:36.081 --> 34:37.952
I barely recognized you.

34:40.542 --> 34:42.541
It's good to see you, Tess.

34:42.542 --> 34:44.541
Yeah?

34:44.542 --> 34:46.542
You, too.

34:52.042 --> 34:54.452
Why did you leave for so long?

35:01.622 --> 35:03.622
I don't know.

35:10.082 --> 35:14.791
But if it... weren't for you...

35:14.792 --> 35:16.792
I might never have come back here.

35:18.372 --> 35:20.372
We're not so bad, are we?

35:23.792 --> 35:25.792
You're not.

35:32.202 --> 35:35.661
HARPER: Mommy, how old is Uncle Garrett?

35:35.662 --> 35:38.041
ALISON: Oh, uh, let me see.

35:38.042 --> 35:39.951
He's 38.

35:39.952 --> 35:42.041
Does he have a girlfriend?

35:42.042 --> 35:43.491
(CHUCKLES)

35:43.492 --> 35:46.791
I... don't know.

35:46.792 --> 35:50.492
Why was he being mean to
Grandpa at the hospital?

35:52.492 --> 35:54.331
He wasn't being mean.

35:54.332 --> 35:56.702
He was telling Grandpa he loved him.

35:57.992 --> 36:00.992
That's not what he said.

36:04.332 --> 36:06.991
Hey, old man.

36:06.992 --> 36:09.831
What did you hear him say?

36:09.832 --> 36:12.121
He said...

36:12.122 --> 36:15.792
I'm gonna tell them it was you.

36:19.832 --> 36:22.252
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

36:28.292 --> 36:30.121
(GROANS)

36:30.122 --> 36:31.952
Maddie?

36:33.792 --> 36:35.792
I'm here, Mitch.

36:37.082 --> 36:39.292
I'm right here.

36:53.992 --> 36:57.412
I think there's something
wrong with Jack.

36:58.992 --> 37:01.411
Of course there is.

37:01.412 --> 37:04.412
He's half me, half you.

37:16.832 --> 37:18.951
(SIGHS)

37:18.952 --> 37:20.952
(HINGES CREAKING)

37:43.952 --> 37:45.952
(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

37:47.162 --> 37:49.752
♪ ♪

38:17.042 --> 38:19.042
(LOW CONVERSATIONS)

38:34.332 --> 38:36.331
We have to tell the truth.

38:36.332 --> 38:37.701
Shh.

38:37.702 --> 38:39.702
Mitch, stop.

38:40.912 --> 38:42.912
We have to.

38:43.992 --> 38:45.992
You need your rest.

38:47.872 --> 38:49.872
(SIGHS)

39:29.992 --> 39:32.412
Maddie.

39:35.452 --> 39:38.081
Just close your eyes...

39:38.082 --> 39:40.491
and relax.

39:40.492 --> 39:43.541
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

39:43.542 --> 39:46.161
I love you.

39:46.162 --> 39:48.992
I can't breathe.

39:55.992 --> 39:57.041
(MITCHELL GAGS QUIETLY)

39:57.042 --> 39:59.751
(BEEPS)

39:59.752 --> 40:02.122
(GASPING)

40:05.292 --> 40:07.292
(GASPS)

40:13.912 --> 40:15.911
(SIGHS)

40:15.912 --> 40:17.621
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

40:17.622 --> 40:19.622
♪ ♪

